  "enhanced_information": "Inherited hyperammonemia is often caused by deficiencies in enzymes involved in the urea cycle, which is crucial for the detoxification of ammonia in the liver. Among the options provided, N-acetyl glutamate synthetase is the only enzyme directly involved in the urea cycle. Deficiency in N-acetyl glutamate synthetase leads to decreased production of N-acetylglutamate, an essential activator of carbamoyl phosphate synthetase I, thereby reducing urea cycle function and resulting in increased ammonia levels, or hyperammonemia. The other enzymes listed - Malate dehydrogenase, Isocitrate dehydrogenase, and Succinate dehydrogenase - are part of the citric acid cycle, not the urea cycle, and their deficiencies do not directly lead to hyperammonemia. The retrieved evidence path regarding septicemia causing hyperammonemia is not directly relevant to the question of enzyme deficiencies in the urea cycle and thus does not aid in answering this specific question."
